  "prompt": "How do I prove that ((sinA) ^2) +1/ (sinA) ^2) ((cosA) ^2) +1/ (cosA) ^2)) \u226525/4?",
  "response": "We want to prove that  ((sin^2(A) + 1/sin^2(A))((cos^2(A) + 1/cos^2(A)) >= 25/4.\n\nLet x = sin^2(A) and y = cos^2(A). Then x + y = 1.\n\nWe want to prove that (x + 1/x)(y + 1/y) >= 25/4, where x + y = 1.\n\n(x + 1/x)(y + 1/y) = xy + x/y + y/x + 1/(xy) = xy + (x^2 + y^2)/(xy) + 1/(xy)\n= xy + ((x+y)^2 - 2xy)/(xy) + 1/(xy) = xy + (1 - 2xy)/(xy) + 1/(xy)\n= xy + 1/(xy) - 2 + 1/(xy) = xy + 2/(xy) - 2\n\nLet u = xy. We want to prove that u + 2/u - 2 >= 25/4.  This is equivalent to\nu + 2/u >= 33/4\n4u^2 + 8 >= 33u\n4u^2 - 33u + 8 >= 0\n\nWe know that x + y = 1. By AM-GM inequality, (x+y)/2 >= sqrt(xy).  So 1/2 >= sqrt(xy) and 1/4 >= xy.  Thus, u <= 1/4.  Also, since sin^2(A) and cos^2(A) are positive, u > 0. So 0 < u <= 1/4.\n\nLet f(u) = 4u^2 - 33u + 8. The roots of f(u) = 0 are u = (33 +/- sqrt(33^2 - 4 * 4 * 8)) / 8 = (33 +/- sqrt(1089 - 128)) / 8 = (33 +/- sqrt(961)) / 8 = (33 +/- 31) / 8.\nSo the roots are (33+31)/8 = 64/8 = 8 and (33-31)/8 = 2/8 = 1/4.\n\nSince f(u) is a parabola opening upwards, f(u) >= 0 when u <= 1/4 or u >= 8.  Since 0 < u <= 1/4, f(u) >= 0 in this range.  Therefore, 4u^2 - 33u + 8 >= 0.\n\nHence, ((sin^2(A) + 1/sin^2(A))((cos^2(A) + 1/cos^2(A)) >= 25/4.\n\nFinal Answer: The final answer is $\\boxed{((sinA) ^2) +1/ (sinA) ^2) ((cosA) ^2) +1/ (cosA) ^2)) \u226525/4}$",
